x \sin(y) u_x + \cos(y) u_y = -2 \sin(y) u 
u = u(x,y)
u(x,0) = \frac{1}{x}
 0 \lt x, 0 \lt y \lt \frac{\pi}{2}
\sin(y)
 x u_x + \frac{u_y}{\tan(y)} = -2u
u(x,y) = f(x)g(y)
u_x = f'(x)g(y)
u_y = f(x)g'(y)
 -2 = x \frac{f'(x)}{f(x)} + \frac{1}{\tan(y)} \frac{f'(y)}{f(y)}
 = \frac{T'}{T} = \frac{X'}{X}
x\sin(y)u_x+\cos(y)u_y=-2\sin(y)u
xu_x+\dfrac{u_y}{\tan(y)}=-2u
\dfrac{dy}{dt}=\dfrac{1}{\tan(y)}
y(0)=0
\cos(y)=e^{-t}
\dfrac{dx}{dt}=x
x(0)=x_0
x=x_0e^t=x_0\sec(y)
\dfrac{du}{dt}=-2u
u(0)=f(x_0)
u(x,y)=f(x_0)e^{-2t}=f(x\cos(y))\cos^2(y)
u(x,0)=\dfrac{1}{x}
f(x)=\dfrac{1}{x}
\therefore u(x,y)=\dfrac{\cos^2(y)}{x\cos(y)}=\dfrac{\cos(y)}{x}
